Use conditional compilation directives in `MauiProgram.cs` to register each platform's implementation:

```csharp
public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

#if ANDROID
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();
#elif IOS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.iOSNotificationService>();
#elif WINDOWS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();
#endif

    return builder.Build();
}
```

Each implementation lives under its respective `Platforms/` folder (which is already platform-filtered by the default `.csproj` ItemGroup globs).

**Alternative** — if you prefer no `#if` directives, use partial classes or the `Microsoft.Maui.Devices` runtime check:

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService>(sp =>
    DeviceInfo.Platform == DevicePlatform.Android ? new AndroidNotificationService() :
    DeviceInfo.Platform == DevicePlatform.iOS     ? new iOSNotificationService() :
    new WindowsNotificationService());
```

The compile-time approach is preferred because it avoids shipping unused platform code and catches missing implementations at build time.
